\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Navarro-Frenk-White mass profile can be normalized respect to the virial
 mass and written in function of the normalized radius respect to the virial
 radius 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{norm}$
\end_inset

 and the concentration 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m_{nfw}\left(r_{norm},c\right)=A\left[\log\left(1+r_{norm}c\right)-\left(\frac{1}{r_{norm}c}+1\right)^{-1}\right]
\]

\end_inset

Where 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a normalization constant such that 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{nfw}\left(1,c\right)=1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
State of Art
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
What did I do?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to obtain a mass profile for each halo in funcion of the radius,
 the center of each halo must be calculated.
 However the center of mass will not give an accurate position for the center
 because some haloes are highly irregular, is more convenient to take the
 gravitational potential for each particle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\left(\boldsymbol{R}_{n}\right)=-\sum_{j\neq n}\frac{1}{\left\Vert \boldsymbol{R}_{n}-\boldsymbol{R}_{j}\right\Vert }
\]

\end_inset

Take 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{R}_{0}=\min\left(\phi\left(\boldsymbol{R}_{n}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 as the center then define new coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{R}_{n}^{\prime}=\boldsymbol{R}_{0}-\boldsymbol{R}_{n}$
\end_inset

, this 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{R}_{0}$
\end_inset

 will be in the most relevant region for the dynamics of each halo.
 Organizing the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{R}_{n}^{\prime}\right\} $
\end_inset

 in crescent order, the accumulated mass for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{R}_{n}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 will be 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n}=nM$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
FIXME: Mass profile of a halo
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then the virial radius is obtained and the particles that are beyond the
 virial radius are removed.
 After that both the mass and the radius get normalized respect to the mass
 and virial radius, we will call these new variables 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The last part of the process consists in fitting the normalized NFW mass
 profile to the 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{n}$
\end_inset

 data using the Metropolis-Hastings algorithm to sample the Likelihood 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal L}\left(c\right)=\exp\left(-\chi^{2}\left(c\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\chi^{2}\left(c\right)=\sum\limits _{n}\left|m_{n}-m_{nfw}\left(r_{n},c\right)\right|^{2}
\]

\end_inset

And taking the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 where the Likelihood is maximum.
 Finally we compare this results with the values obtaned by BDM, since the
 number of halos obtained by FOF and BDM is different, each BDM halo gets
 related with the nearest halo in FOF.
 We compute two concentrations, one where the overdensity limit is 
\begin_inset Formula $360\rho_{back}$
\end_inset

 (like in BDMV) an other where the overdensity limit is 
\begin_inset Formula $740\rho_{back}$
\end_inset

 (like in BDMW).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Trial Problem with several Generated Halos
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To be sure that the results are reasonable, several tests were performed
 generating halos from the Navarro-Frenk-White profile with known values
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{s}.$
\end_inset

 The center of the generated halos is 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{0}=\left(0,0,0\right)$
\end_inset

 so we can determine how good estimate is the minimum of the potential at
 the center of each halo.
 Two types of tests were run: The first omitting the calculation of the
 center of each halo and assuming that is 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{0}$
\end_inset

 and second by calculating the center as the minimum of the potential.
\end_layout

